{When I saw Sergiy Didukh's study in 2009, it left an impression to me, maybe
not for its other merits but for the depth of its idea. How does the lone king
manage to outmanoeuver two knights?  We will see it in this study: White to
move and draw!} 1. Rb2+ $1 ({Importantly, the other possible move does not
work:} 1. Rb1 $2 Nf3+ 2. Ke4 Ne1 3. Rb2+ Kc3 $19 ({for example} 3... Kc3 4.
Rxf2 Nxf2+ 5. Kf4 Ned3+ 6. Kg5 Ne4+ 7. Kh6 Nf6 $19)) 1... Kc1 2. Ra2 $1 {The
black king is lured to b1!} ({Thematic wrong try:} 2. Rxf2 $2 Nxf2 3. Ke3 Nh3
4. b6 Nf5+ 5. Kf3 Nd6 6. Kg4 Nf2+ 7. Kh5 Nfe4 8. Kh6 Nf6 9. Kg7 h5 10. Kxf6 h4
11. Ke5 h3 12. Kxd6 h2 13. b7 h1=Q 14. b8=Q {(position X with Kc1)} Qh2+ $19)
2... Kb1 3. Rxf2 Nxf2 4. Ke3 $1 ({White must try to capture Ph7 (via
d4-e3-f4-g5-h6) because moving the own pawn does not work immediately:} 4. b6
$2 Nf5+ $1 5. Ke5 Ne7 6. Kf6 Nc6 7. Kg5 Ne4+ 8. Kh6 Nf6 9. Kg7 h5 10. Kxf6 h4
$19) 4... Nh3 {Black prevents the plan, but now the knight is too far away
from the pawn. Preventing this would cost the other knight.} (4... Ng4+ 5. Kf4
Nf6 6. Kg5 Nd7 7. Kxh4 $11) 5. b6 Nf5+ {Of course, the other knight now needs
to catch the passed pawn.} 6. Kf3 $1 ({The direct approach does not work, and
Black has multiple winning way then, for example} 6. Ke4 Nd6+ 7. Kd5 Nb7 8. Kc6
{Is this not a draw?} {No, there is the other knight!} Nf4 $1 9. Kxb7 Nd5 $19)
6... Nd6 ({In the other case, we see a kind of Réti manoeuver.} 6... Nd4+ 7.
Kg4 Nf2+ 8. Kg5 Ne4+ 9. Kh6 Nf6 10. Kg7 h5 11. Kxf6 h4 12. Ke5 h3 13. Kxd4 $11)
7. Kg4 Nf2+ 8. Kh5 $1 ({While the moves seem equal, in fact the square must be
chosen carefully.} 8. Kg5 $2 Nf7+ $1 9. Kh5 (9. Kf6 Nd8 10. Kg5 Ne4+ 11. Kh6
Nf6 $19) 9... Ne4 10. b7 Nf6+ 11. Kh4 Nd7 $19) 8... Nfe4 9. Kh6 Nf6 10. Kg7 $1
Nde8+ 11. Kh6 Nd6 12. Kg7 h5 13. Kxf6 h4 14. Ke5 h3 15. Kxd6 h2 16. b7 h1=Q 17.
b8=Q+ {(position X with Kb1)} 1/2-1/2

