{This study is one that after its first publication became famous. In my
opinion, the late Georgian master was right in his assessment to crown it as
the winner in his 1997 jubilee tourney. White is a piece up but faces two
dangerous passed pawns. Things are complicated because the extra piece is
pinned and if White theatens checkmate on b5, Black will just give a check on
h5 and win the piece back. So what can be done as White is to move and draw?} 
1. Nc3 Rh5+ {Black wins the piece back, keeps his dangerous passed pawns, and
it seems hopeless to continue the battle at first. Won't Black, even in the
worst case, just be able to give a rook and still win with his pawns? What can
White hope for?} 2. f5 $3 ({To understand White's ingenious move, we will have
to look at how the game could continue: TWT} 2. Nb5+ $2 Rxb5+ 3. Kxb5 Rxa1 4.
Re7+ Kb8 5. a7+ Ka8 6. Ka6 (6. Kb6 Rb1+ 7. Ka6 Rb8 8. axb8=Q+ Kxb8 9. Kb6 Kc8
10. Kc6 Kd8 11. Kd6 g2 12. Rg7 Ke8 13. Kxe6 Kf8 14. Kf6 h2 15. Rxg2 h1=Q $19)
6... Rxa3+ 7. Kb6 Rb3+ 8. Ka6 Rb8 9. axb8=Q+ Kxb8 10. Kb6 Kc8 11. Kc6 Kd8 12.
Kd6 g2 13. Ra7 Kc8 14. Kc6 Kb8 15. Ra1 h2 16. Rb1+ Kc8 17. Ra1 Kd8 18. Kd6 Ke8
19. Kxe6 Kf8 20. Kf6 Kg8 21. Ra8+ Kh7 22. Ra7+ Kh6 23. Ra8 Kh5 24. Kf5 Kh4 $19)
2... Rxf5+ 3. Nb5+ Rxb5+ 4. Kxb5 Rxa1 {Things still look gloomy for White, but
the pawn on a6 allows enough counterplay.} 5. Re7+ Kb8 6. a7+ Ka8 7. Ka6 $3 {
Another great move gets rid of Pa3, the piece that would block the path for
the rook later.} ({TWT} 7. Kb6 $2 Rb1+ 8. Ka6 Rb8 $1 9. axb8=Q+ Kxb8 10. Kb6
Kc8 11. Kc6 Kd8 12. Kd6 g2 13. Ra7 (13. Rg7 Ke8 14. Kxe6 Kf8 15. Kf6 h2 16.
Rxg2 h1=Q $19) 13... Kc8 14. Kc6 Kb8 $19) 7... Rxa3+ 8. Kb6 Rb3+ 9. Ka6 Rb8 $1
10. axb8=Q+ {(or any other promotion)} Kxb8 11. Kb6 Kc8 12. Kc6 Kd8 13. Kd6 $1
g2 $1 14. Ra7 Kc8 15. Kc6 ({White can reverse the next two moves, this is a
minor dual that does not destroy the study.} 15. Ra1 h2 16. Kc6 $18) 15... Kb8
16. Ra1 ({Giving the check on b7 wastes time, another minor dual or waste of
time dual. Experts are divided on which one it is in a draw study, but agree
that it does not destroy the study either usually.} 16. Rb7+ Ka8 17. Rb1 h2 18.
Ra1+ Kb8 19. Rb1+ Kc8 20. Ra1 Kd8 $11 {and onwards like after 18.-Kd8 in the
text.}) 16... h2 ({Otherwise the draw is easier:} 16... e5 $2 17. Rb1+ Kc8 18.
Ra1 Kd8 19. Kd6 Ke8 20. Ke6 Kf8 21. Kf6 Kg8 22. Kg6 $11) 17. Rb1+ Kc8 18. Ra1
Kd8 19. Kd6 Ke8 20. Kxe6 Kf8 21. Kf6 Kg8 22. Ra8+ Kh7 23. Ra7+ Kh6 24. Ra8 Kh5
25. Kf5 Kh4 {Now we see why White sacrificed the pawn on f4. He needed that
square 24 moves later for his king.} 26. Kf4 Kh5 27. Kf5 $11 {and the draw by
threefold repetition is unavoidable unless Black wants to be checkmated.}
1/2-1/2

